Fred (f ... @hotmailx.com) writes:
> On 14 Mar 2007 13:03:39 GMT, a ... @FreeNet.Carleton.CA (James Roots)
> wrote:

>>Thanks, everyone.

>>Now, if you would like to know how anything is &quot;pronounced&quot;
>>in ASL, feel free to ask me!

>>Jim

> I do have a question:  How is different emphasis or inflections
> handled?  For example:

> WHAT are you doing?

> What ARE you doing?

> What are YOU doing?

> What are you DOING?
">

This assumes we are signing a specific sign for each word.  That
doesn't happen in ASL.

"What are you doing?" is signed in its entirety with a single
sign -- the "DO-DO" sign.  Palm turned inward, the 3 outer
fingers folded flat against the palm, and the upraised index
finger and thumb tapping against each other.  It is supposed
to represent fingerspelling the letters D-O, but over time it
has become "lazy signing" so it's hard to see the letters now.
The tapping is why it isn't just "the DO sign" but rather the
"DO-DO" sign -- repetition of the gesture.

With such a simple sign, all emphasis comes through the face.
A friendly or indifferent expression turns it into a routine
query like "How are you this morning?"  Cocked eyebrows turn
it into the puzzled, "What the heck are you doing?"  A scowl
or frown turn it into a demand,  "WHAT THE HELL DO YOU THINK
YOU'RE DOING?!?!"

We would almost never emphasize conjunctives like "are".  These
terms don't exist in real ASL.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
> Each of those variations has a slightly different meaning, even to the
> point of some (like the first and last) implying a degree of anger.
> Does sign language deal with that?  Is it simply the look on the
> signer's face?  Are sarcasm and things like that handled the same way?
">

Yeah.  For sarcasms, I would tilt my head back a little, put a
bit of a sneer or snicker on my mouth, and "DO-DO?" in a
"c'mon, you little putz, what are you trying to pull?" manner.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
> By the way, PBS here has a short little show on in the mornings that
> teaches young kids sign language and our 4 year-old loves it.  She's
> learned quite a few words.  Between her English vocabulary, sign
> language vocabulary, and Spanish vocabulary (from Dora The Explorer),
> she's getting to be quite a little language expert.
">

The other day I was stunned to see two entire bookshelves filled
with baby/infant Sign books at my local bookstore.  But I would
advise you to avoid the Disney crap from Baby Einstein.  Go for
the stuff from small presses that were produced by Deaf people
you never heard of (i.e., not Linda Bove or Marlee Matlin).
It's not that Linda or Marlee are not authentic Signers, it's
that they have been forced to peddle stuff that is actually
Seeing Exact English (SEE) rather than real ASL.  SEE is not
a language, it is a "sign system" artificially created to
equate one English word with one sign.  And as I think I've
made clear in this posting, ASL doesn't work on a one-to-one
basis with English.

Jim
